    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-05-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-05-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="462"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d462">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6359/5–2747: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-05-27">May 27,
                            1947</date>.<lb/>[Received June 4—9:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–112. Following is Tihwa’s 222, May 24, 9 p.m.:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Mytel 215, May 22, section 3: <hi rend="italic">c</hi>) Russia might also be
                        motivated by need for certain strategic minerals reported to exist in this
                        Province, presumably thoroughly explored by the several Soviet mineralogical
                        advisers to Sheng Shih-tsai. Wusu oil wells are still working
                        (antepenultimate para Mytel 184 May 9<note n="23" xml:id="d462fn1">Not
                            printed.</note>) and were observed with binoculars as we passed. There
                        are said to be considerable wolfram deposits in Ashan zone (mytel 74, Mar
                            7<note n="23" xml:id="d462fn2">Not printed.</note>) already being
                        exploited by Russian engineers as well as some mines near Borotola,
                        variously claimed to be of iron or some unidentified heavy mineral (Clubb’s
                        despatch 20, July 28, 1943<note n="25" xml:id="d462fn3">Not printed, but see
                            despatch No. 1449, August 9, 1943, from the Ambassador in China, <ref
                                target="frus1943China#pg_312">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, China, p. 312</ref>.
                            O. Edmund Clubb, Second Secretary of Embassy in China, was detailed as
                            Consul at Tihwa in 1943.</note>) conceivably uranium, though we saw no
                        signs of operation on our way. Should any deposits of this ore exist, they
                        alone would of course be enough to account for Soviet interest. USSR might
                        accordingly be willing to make considerable temporary ideological <pb
                            facs="0566" n="556" xml:id="pg_556"/> compromise and even forego
                        immediate political sovereignty, allowing the natives assemblage or the
                        independence they desire (mytel 202, May 15<note n="26" xml:id="d462fn4">Not
                            printed.</note>), provided Russian extraction of ores is permitted to
                        continue. Chinese Central Govt could hardly be expected to consent to this
                        if they exert eventual control over production areas as they do not now.
                        Section 4 follows. Paxton.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
